            . I am a <rs id="t18291029-239-viclabel1352" type="occupation">weaver</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18291029-239-victim1935 t18291029-239-viclabel1352"></join>. Last Wednesday I was called to dinner at five minutes before twelve o'clock, and left the watch in the window of the workshop; when I came up in about half an hour it was gone, and the prisoner likewise; he had worked there about six weeks - he gave himself up the next day.</p>
               <p>ELIZA MORRIS. I am in the prosecutor's service. My master went down to dinner, and the prisoner sent me out of the shop; I was gone about five minutes, and when I returned he was gone.</p>
               <p>WILLIAM CLAMP. I am a pawnbroker. I have a watch pawned with me by the prisoner on Wednesday, between twelve and one o'clock - our house is more than a mile from the prosecutor's.</p>
               <p>JAMES HANLEY. The prisoner came and surrendered himself to me last Thursday, and told me where he had pawned the watch.(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
